Step 7 of the project outline involves adding keyboard controls to allow the user to move and rotate the current Tetromino.

To accomplish this, you can add a new method called `handleKeyPress` to the `TetrisGame` class. This method will be called whenever a key is pressed, and it will check which key was pressed and update the current Tetromino accordingly. Here's the code for the `handleKeyPress` method:
```java
private void handleKeyPress(KeyCode code) {
    if (currentTetromino != null) {
        switch (code) {
            case LEFT:
                if (canTetrominoMove(currentTetromino, -1, 0)) {
                    currentTetromino.move(-1, 0);
                }
                break;
            case RIGHT:
                if (canTetrominoMove(currentTetromino, 1, 0)) {
                    currentTetromino.move(1, 0);
                }
                break;
            case UP:
                if (canTetrominoRotate(currentTetromino)) {
                    currentTetromino.rotate();
                }
                break;
            case DOWN:
                if (canTetrominoMove(currentTetromino, 0, 1)) {
                    currentTetromino.move(0, 1);
                }
                break;
            default:
                // do nothing
                break;
        }
        display.update(gameBoard, currentTetromino, score);
    }
}
```
This code uses a `switch` statement to check which key was pressed (represented by the `KeyCode` enum). If the left arrow key is pressed and the current Tetromino can move left, it moves left by calling the `move` method with arguments `-1` for the x direction and `0` for the y direction. Similarly, if the right arrow key is pressed and the current Tetromino can move right, it moves right by calling `move` with arguments `1` for the x direction and `0` for the y direction.

If the up arrow key is pressed and the current Tetromino can rotate, it rotates by calling the `rotate` method. Finally, if the down arrow key is pressed and the current Tetromino can move down, it moves down by calling `move` with arguments `0` for the x direction and `1` for the y direction.

You can add an event handler for key presses to the `start` method using the `setOnKeyPressed` method of the game board `Scene`. Here's the updated `start` method:
