In programming, an interface is a type of contract that specifies a set of methods and properties that a class must implement. The purpose of an interface is to define a standard way of interacting with objects that have different implementations.

In C#, `IList<T>` is an interface that defines a set of methods and properties that a class must implement to be considered a list. However, an interface itself cannot be instantiated, meaning you cannot create an object directly from an interface.

Instead, you need to create an instance of a class that implements the `IList<T>` interface. In this case, you can use the `List<T>` class which implements the `IList<T>` interface. The `List<T>` class provides an implementation for the methods and properties defined by the `IList<T>` interface.

Here's an example to help illustrate this concept:
```csharp
// Define a class that implements the IList<T> interface
class MyList<T> : IList<T>
{
    // Implement the required methods and properties here
}

// This will cause a compiler error because you can't create an instance of an interface directly
IList<string> myList = new IList<string>();

// This creates an instance of the MyList<T> class, which implements the IList<T> interface
MyList<string> myList = new MyList<string>();

// This creates an instance of the List<T> class, which also implements the IList<T> interface
List<string> myList = new List<string>();
```
So in your example code, you can replace `new IList<FailureMessage>()` with `new List<FailureMessage>()` to create a new list that implements the `IList<FailureMessage>` interface.

Sure, here's an example of how to use a reusable barrier in C++ using the `std::barrier` class from the C++20 standard library:
```c
#include <iostream>
#include <thread>
#include <barrier>

const int THREAD_COUNT = 4;
std::barrier reusable_barrier(THREAD_COUNT);

void thread_function(int thread_id) {
  std::cout << "Thread " << thread_id << " started." << std::endl;

  // Perform some work...
  // ...

  std::cout << "Thread " << thread_id << " reached the barrier." << std::endl;
  reusable_barrier.arrive_and_wait(); // Wait for all threads to reach the barrier

  // Perform some more work...
  // ...

  std::cout << "Thread " << thread_id << " finished." << std::endl;
}

int main() {
  std::thread threads[THREAD_COUNT];

  // Create threads and execute them
  for (int i = 0; i < THREAD_COUNT; i++) {
    threads[i] = std::thread(thread_function, i);
  }

  // Wait for all threads to finish
  for (int i = 0; i < THREAD_COUNT; i++) {
    threads[i].join();
  }

  std::cout << "All threads finished." << std::endl;

  return 0;
}
```
In this example, we define a reusable barrier using the `std::barrier` class and specify the number of threads that will be using it. In the `thread_function`, each thread performs some work, reaches the barrier, and waits for all other threads to reach the barrier before continuing. Finally, after all threads have finished executing, the main thread joins each of the threads and exits.

