Using `class-validator` with TypeScript is a great way to define and validate your Firestore database schemas. `class-validator` provides a decorator-based syntax for defining your data models, which makes it easy to read and maintain your code.

Here's an example of how you might define a data model for a user document in TypeScript using `class-validator`:
```typescript
import { IsDefined, IsEmail, IsString } from 'class-validator';

class User {
  @IsDefined()
  @IsString()
  name!: string;

  @IsDefined()
  @IsEmail()
  email!: string;

  @IsDefined()
  @IsString()
  password!: string;

  constructor(name: string, email: string, password: string) {
    this.name = name;
    this.email = email;
    this.password = password;
  }
}
```
In this example, we're using decorators like `@IsDefined()`, `@IsString()`, and `@IsEmail()` to define the validation rules for our `User` class. We're also defining a constructor that sets the values of our class properties.

You can use this `User` class in conjunction with the `firestore-admin` package to create new user documents in your Firestore database. Here's an example of how you might do this:
```typescript
import * as admin from 'firebase-admin';
import { validate } from 'class-validator';

async function createUser(name: string, email: string, password: string) {
  const db = admin.firestore();
  const user = new User(name, email, password);

  const errors = await validate(user);

  if (errors.length > 0) {
    console.error(errors);
    throw new Error('Validation failed');
  }

  await db.collection('users').doc(email).set(user);
}
```
In this example, we're creating a new `User` object with the provided `name`, `email`, and `password` values. We're then using the `validate` function from `class-validator` to check that the object meets the validation rules we defined in our `User` class.

