Firestore's `withConverter` method can be used to automatically convert Firestore documents to and from custom classes. You can use this feature to run your validations and define your Firestore schemas in a single place.

Here's an example of how you might define a `User` class using `class-validator` and use `withConverter` to automatically validate and convert Firestore documents:
```typescript
import * as admin from 'firebase-admin';
import { IsDefined, IsEmail, IsString, validate } from 'class-validator';

class User {
  @IsDefined()
  @IsString()
  name!: string;

  @IsDefined()
  @IsEmail()
  email!: string;

  @IsDefined()
  @IsString()
  password!: string;

  constructor(name: string, email: string, password: string) {
    this.name = name;
    this.email = email;
    this.password = password;
  }

  static fromFirestore(snapshot: admin.firestore.DocumentSnapshot<User>): User {
    const data = snapshot.data();
    return new User(data.name, data.email, data.password);
  }

  static toFirestore(user: User): admin.firestore.DocumentData {
    const errors = validate(user);

    if (errors.length > 0) {
      console.error(errors);
      throw new Error('Validation failed');
    }

    return {
      name: user.name,
      email: user.email,
      password: user.password,
    };
  }
}

const userConverter = {
  toFirestore: User.toFirestore,
  fromFirestore: User.fromFirestore,
};

const db = admin.firestore();
const userRef = db.collection('users').doc('example@example.com').withConverter(userConverter);

// Create a new user document
const newUser = new User('Alice', 'example@example.com', 'password');
await userRef.set(newUser);

// Get an existing user document
const userDoc = await userRef.get();
const user = userDoc.data();
console.log(user);
```
In this example, we're defining a `User` class with validation rules using `class-validator`. We're also defining `toFirestore` and `fromFirestore` methods to convert between Firestore documents and our `User` class.

We're then creating a Firestore document reference using the `withConverter` method and passing in our `userConverter` object. This will automatically validate and convert the document data to our `User` class.

Finally, we're creating a new `User` object, setting it as the data for our Firestore document reference, and retrieving the document data using the `get()` method.

