If you want to validate your data on the read side as well, you can define a custom `fromFirestore` method for your `User` class that includes validation logic. Here's an example of how you might modify the `fromFirestore` method to include validation:
```typescript
class User {
  @IsDefined()
  @IsString()
  name!: string;

  @IsDefined()
  @IsEmail()
  email!: string;

  @IsDefined()
  @IsString()
  password!: string;

  constructor(name: string, email: string, password: string) {
    this.name = name;
    this.email = email;
    this.password = password;
  }

  static fromFirestore(
    snapshot: admin.firestore.QueryDocumentSnapshot<User> | admin.firestore.DocumentSnapshot<User>,
    options?: admin.firestore.SnapshotOptions
  ): User {
    const data = snapshot.data(options);

    const user = new User(data.name, data.email, data.password);

    const errors = validate(user);

    if (errors.length > 0) {
      console.error(errors);
      throw new Error('Validation failed');
    }

    return user;
  }

  static toFirestore(user: User): admin.firestore.DocumentData {
    return {
      name: user.name,
      email: user.email,
      password: user.password,
    };
  }
}
```
In this modified `User` class, we've added a custom `fromFirestore` method that includes validation logic using `class-validator`. When a Firestore document is retrieved using this method, the data is validated and an error is thrown if the data is invalid.

